approach is academic, not devotional.....They must not give primacy to any particular faith.&quot; Providing a prayer room is not an &quot;accommodation&quot;. It is using public school space for the practice of religion, which is illegal. Prayer is devotional and therefore, organized prayer time in a school is illegal. Only one particular faith is pursuing this prayer room, meaning that one particular faith is receiving primacy and is therefore illegal. &#10;Finally, the real issue was that children between the ages of 10 to 14 were not returning to school after their Friday prayer. That's a discipline and truancy issue and should be dealt with as such, with the individuals and their parents. The entire school should not be expected to pander to entitled brats who decide to skip off from school. If it was a real issue, a community leader ought to have identified the problem and taken the initiative to supervise the return of students to school. The current strategy only serves to stratify the students, which will result in alienation and resentment among both the Muslim and Non-Muslim students. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1396" language="en" documentId="1222" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Womanwhocares" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/tempers-flare-over-prayer-in-schools-1.1104775" topic="prayer-in-schools" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="1222" notes="" title="Tempers flare over prayer in schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="746"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="747" end="1396"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43"/></xmi:XMI>